dataset.description: Election results by precinct for Stark County, Ohio from the primary election held on Tuesday, May 8, 2018. These results include races for federal, state, county, and local issues. The Stark County Board of Elections (BOE) maintains the precincts layer for the county, which are identified in the attribute table. The results for each race are compiled into this single layer for convenience. The attribute table also contains information on voter turnout and registration.
dataset.title: 2018 Primary Election Results

dataset.description: This dataset represents Sewer Manholes in the Stark County sanitary sewer system. Most features were placed with a handheld GPS unit with +/- 3 ft accuracy. Digital data can be made available as an ESRI geodatabase or shapefile. Users must have ArcGIS software to view data.

dataset.description:
A discharge point is essential what is called an outfall.  An outfall is where a pipe or ditch 
enter into a creek, stream, river, basin, lake or pond; or any other area deemed 
a water of the state.  These points are check yearly for illicit discharge.
dataset.title: Stormwater - Discharge Points

Digital data can be made available as an ESRI geodatabase or shapefile. Users must have ArcGIS software to view data.

dataset.description: A gravity main is a pipe in varying sizes that carries storm water by means of gravity. This essentially means there is no artificial machine used to move the storm water.
dataset.title: Stormwater - Gravity Mains

dataset.description:
An inlet is basically called a catch basin.  There are usually 2 types of 
inlets.  A side inlet, which you see adjacent to a curb and grated inlets that 
occur almost everyplace else.  Inlets collect storm water runoff and carry it by 
way of pipes and ditches to the 
outfall.
dataset.title: Stormwater - Inlets

dataset.description: Line layer consisting of roads within Stark County, Ohio.
dataset.title: Roads

dataset.description:
A Storm water manhole is a small covered opening in the pavement or other 
surface that allows a person to enter the storm water chamber beneath the manhole cover.  This chamber is usually a concrete chamber with one or several 
pipes entering and leaving the chamber.  These pipes carry storm water runoff 
into and out of the chamber.
dataset.title: Stormwater - Manholes

dataset.description:
Detention areas are a basin in an area where excess storm water is stored or 
held temporarily.  Retention basins hold water and Detention basins slowly drain 
when water levels in the receiving channel recede.
dataset.title: Stormwater - Detention Areas

dataset.description: A formula was used and data was compiled to render the level of difficulty. This formula consisted of daily traffic volume, daily truck volume, posted speed limits and the number of lanes. Also included in a lesser weight were: turning lanes, on street bike lanes and parking availability.
dataset.title: Ride Stark - Level of Difficulty

dataset.description:
A flood control facility refers to any method used to prevent or reduce the 
detrimental effects of flood waters.  This may include, but not limited 
to; planting vegetation, construction of flood ways, levees, lakes, dams, 
reservoirs or retention/detention ponds.
dataset.title: Stormwater - Flood Control Facilities
